          "body": "The chapter opens with a jarring qualification: Reuben was the firstborn, but his birthright had been reassigned (5:1-2). The Chronicler feels the weight of the record — he cannot simply list Reuben's sons as if nothing had happened. Reuben's sin against his father's concubine Bilhah (Genesis 35:22; 49:3-4) disqualified him from the double-portion and leadership that belonged to the firstborn. Jacob's dying words had already announced the verdict: 'You shall not have preeminence' (Genesis 49:4). The Chronicler preserves the genealogy — Reuben still has sons, still has a tribe, still has territory — but under the shadow of what could have been. This is the chapter's first theological claim: covenant privilege is not unconditional. Moral failure has multigenerational consequences, and the Chronicler will not airbrush them out. Yet the tribe is not abandoned; the genealogy is still kept, the name is still enrolled. Judgment and preservation coexist. The same pattern will close the chapter: exile is real and ongoing, but the names are still recorded, the history is still told, the covenantal relationship is still the frame within which the story makes sense."
