          "body": "The word that changes everything in this chapter is the single Hebrew verb maal — 'they acted treacherously' (5:25). It is the Chronicler's sharpest covenant-violation vocabulary, appearing repeatedly across Chronicles to explain military defeats and divine abandonments (2 Chronicles 12:2; 28:19; 36:14). Here it pivots the chapter from the heights of prayer-answered victory (5:20-22) and the prestige of famous warriors (5:24) to the humiliation of idolatry and exile. The specific form of the treachery is named without euphemism: they 'played the harlot after the gods of the peoples of the land, whom God had destroyed before them' (5:25). The prophetic vocabulary of zanah (to play the harlot) places this within the marriage-and-adultery metaphor that runs through Hosea, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel — Israel's relationship with God was covenantal and intimate, and idolatry was its sexual betrayal. The Chronicler underlines the absurdity with a participial phrase: these were the gods 'whom God had destroyed before them.' The tribes ran after defeated deities, abandoning the God who had just given them an overwhelming victory. The chapter's military narrative exists to make this irony cutting. You cannot read 5:25 without hearing the echo of 5:20 — 'they trusted in Him' has become 'they played the harlot after other gods.'"
